         <Summary>TBoldTreeView allows displaying and optionally editing information from the Business Object tier of Bold.</Summary>
         <Desc> <See Class="TBoldCustomTreeView" Property="BoldHandle" Text="BoldHandle"/> specifies the root of the tree and the sub-properties of <See Class="TBoldCustomTreeView" Property="BoldProperties" Text="BoldPropeties"/> specify how the value is to be displayed and edited.
            <P>To display a node in a TreeView you need to have three things. A string for the node's text, an integer to select which icon to show from the Images property and optionally a list of elements to create child nodes from.</P>
            <BH>Node Description Editor</BH>
Double click on the TBoldTreeView to show the Node Description Editor. Create new Node Descriptions with the [Add Node Description] button or select an existing Node Description in the tree.
A TBoldNodeDescription has a <See Class="TBoldNodeDescription" Property="TextController" Text="TextController"/> to control the text of a node, an <See Class="TBoldNodeDescription" Property="IconController" Text="IconController"/> to control the index of the node's image and a <See Class="TBoldNodeDescription" Property="ListController" Text="ListController"/> to control the child nodes.
            <P>The example below illustrates configuration of a BoldTreeView using the model in the Building Example found in the examples directory.</P>
            <P>Every Node Description are usually designed for different contexts. Use the Name property to give the Node Description a Name that reflects the context. If the context of a node is a Person set the Name property to Person.
The TextController.Expression could be 
               <Code>lastname+', '+firstname+' ('+age.asStrring+')'</Code>
 to show the lastname, firstname and age.</P>
            <P>If all persons use the same image from the images list then the IconController.Expression could be a constant (i.e. "12") or 
               <Code>if assets > 10000 then 13 else 12 endif</Code>
 to show a different icon depending on how rich the person is.
The ListController has a collection of Parts and every part describes a fragment of a list of elements. Click on the [Add List Fragment] button to create a new part of the list or select an existing from the tree.</P>
            <P>The ElementExpression of a part has the same context as the expression in the TextController and IconController. It is used to evaluate a new context of a child node. It could be "Home" to create a child node for the Building where the Person lives.</P>
            <P>Set the InterpretAsList property to True if the ElementExpression evaluates to a list. If the ElementExpression is "OwnedBuildings" and InterpretAsList is True, a new child node will be created for every Building in the list. The context of each child node will be a Building. If InterpretAsList is false only one child node will be created. The context of that child node will be a list of Buildings.</P>
            <P>The ControllerExpression is used to find a Node Description to the child nodes. It is evaluated in the same context as the child node itself. The result should be a string that matches the Name property of a NodeDescription. It could be "'OwnedBuildings'" to choose a NodeDescription named OwnedBuildings or "self.oclType" to choose a NodeDescription with the same name as the current context.</P>
         </Desc>
